    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "My solution was to create a widget that checks each refinement widget for an active state, and if it has one, open it up:\r\n```javascript\r\nconst options = this.options;\r\nlet once = true;\r\n\r\nvar openIfRefined = function openIfRefined() {\r\n  return {\r\n    render: function() {\r\n      // Check each refinement widget for an active filter and open it if so\r\n      if (once) { // Only once or this will happen each interaction with the widget\r\n        $(\".search-refine > div\").each((index, elem) => {\r\n          let refineWidget = $(elem);\r\n          let isOpen = refineWidget\r\n            .find(\".ais-refinement-list--item\")\r\n            .hasClass(\"ais-refinement-list--item__active\");\r\n          if (isOpen) {\r\n            refineWidget\r\n              .find(\".ais-root__collapsible\")\r\n              .removeClass(\"ais-root__collapsed\");\r\n            refineWidget.find(\".panel-heading\").trigger(\"click\");\r\n          }\r\n        });\r\n        once = false;\r\n      }\r\n    }\r\n  };\r\n};\r\n\r\nthis.search.addWidget(openIfRefined());\r\n```\r\nThe React component has its state set to `collapsed: true`. I don't know anything about react, is there any way to update the react component's state externally of the framework?\r\n\r\nRight now I am triggering click on load to set it to the correct state in a roundabout way:\r\n```javascript\r\n ...\r\n refineWidget.find('.panel-heading').trigger('click');\r\n ...\r\n```",
    "created_at": "2017-07-31T18:08:16Z",
